{"title":"Verizon will take your damaged iPhone off your hands for $1,000","link":"https://www.macworld.com/article/342253/verizon-will-take-your-damaged-iphone-off-your-hands-for-1000.html","date":1617286180000,"content":"<!DOCTYPE html PUBLIC \"-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.0 Transitional//EN\" \"http://www.w3.org/TR/REC-html40/loose.dtd\">\n<html><body><div id=\"link_wrapped_content\">\n<section class=\"wp-block-bigbite-multi-title\"><div class=\"container\"></div></section><p>It may be rolling out on April Fool&rsquo;s Day, but Verizon claims its new promotion isn&rsquo;t a joke: starting today, <a href=\"https://go.redirectingat.com/?id=111346X1569486&amp;url=https://www.verizon.com/about/news/you-broke-your-phone-so-verizon-breaking-rules&amp;xcust=1-1-342253-0-0-0&amp;sref=https://www.macworld.com/feed\" data-type=\"URL\" data-id=\"https://www.verizon.com/about/news/you-broke-your-phone-so-verizon-breaking-rules\" rel=\"nofollow\">Verizon will give you up to $1,000</a> for your &ldquo;cracked or water damaged phone.&rdquo; We tested it out and it seems to be a very good deal, so if you&rsquo;re tempted to dig out your busted iPhone from the bottom of your cable drawer, there are a few things you should know.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Like most carrier deals, Verizon isn&rsquo;t going to handing everyone checks for $1,000. The trade-in is actually $700, with the remainder coming in the form of a $300 Verizon gift card. If you qualify for the full amount, the remaining $700 trade-in value divided among 24 equal bill credits. Existing subscribers are eligible for $440 in savings as long as they add a new line to their account.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>You&rsquo;ll also need to sign up for one of <a href=\"https://go.redirectingat.com/?id=111346X1569486&amp;url=https://www.verizon.com/plans/unlimited/?cmp=KNC-C-HQ-NON-R-BP-NONE-MNMEntDisneyBundleEnglish-2K0VZ0-COE-GAW-71700000071414699&amp;#038;gclid=CjwKCAjw3pWDBhB3EiwAV1c5rGjz4wj22bpUI9R6VTWFNjTa1TThauRBFrRhKO3DhcPL-Ze2twb9HhoCREoQAvD_BwE&amp;#038;gclsrc=aw.ds&amp;xcust=1-1-342253-0-0-0&amp;sref=https://www.macworld.com/feed\" data-type=\"URL\" data-id=\"https://www.verizon.com/plans/unlimited/?cmp=KNC-C-HQ-NON-R-BP-NONE-MNMEntDisneyBundleEnglish-2K0VZ0-COE-GAW-71700000071414699&amp;gclid=CjwKCAjw3pWDBhB3EiwAV1c5rGjz4wj22bpUI9R6VTWFNjTa1TThauRBFrRhKO3DhcPL-Ze2twb9HhoCREoQAvD_BwE&amp;gclsrc=aw.ds\" rel=\"nofollow\">Verizon&rsquo;s 5G ultra wideband unlimited plans</a> which start at $80 a month (plus taxes and fees) for a single line and drop to as low as $40 a month for five lines or more. Other caveats are you&rsquo;ll need to buy a phone that costs at least $849.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>For safety reasons, Verizon won&rsquo;t accept phones with swollen batteries, but otherwise, there are surprisingly few restrictions to what can be traded in. Basically anything goes. I checked several iPhones that were cracked and wouldn&rsquo;t power on and I got the full amount every time, up to the iPhone 8 and including the iPhone SE. It dipped from $700 to $350 for the iPhone 7 and 6, which is still very good.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Verizon says the offer is only available for a limited time, so if you&rsquo;ve been looking to switch carriers, this might be a reason to jump. Click on the Verizon link below to start the process.</p>\n\n\n\n\t\t<div class=\"wp-block-product-widget-block product-widget\">\n\t\t\t<div class=\"product-widget__block-title-wrapper\">\n\t\t\t\t<h4 class=\"product-widget__block-title\" id=\"\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t</h4>\n\t\t\t</div>\n\n\t\t\t<div class=\"product-widget__content-wrapper\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<div class=\"product-widget__title-wrapper\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<h3 class=\"product-widget__title\" id=\"iphone-12-pro-max\">iPhone 12 Pro Max</h3>\n\t\t\t\t\t</div>\n\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<div class=\"product-widget__image-outer-wrapper\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<div class=\"product-widget__image-wrapper\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<img class=\"product-widget__image\" src=\"https://images.idgesg.net/images/article/2020/11/i